I"<<p>If the phenomenal space is the state space of all possible <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/phenomenal-representations-are-experienced-mental-representations">experiences</a>, then one can note that it’s adapted to the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/representationism-in-cognition-is-adaptationism-in-evolution">needs of the organism</a>. It’s <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/contrasting-difficulties-are-like-price-decoys">easy</a> to <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/visual-imagery-brightness-modulates-pupil-size">imagine</a> eating than solving differential equations. Ease of imagining, or conceivability, might be a probe for <span title="There is no note that matches this link." class="invalid-link">
  <span class="invalid-link-brackets">[[</span>
  Phenomenal (re)presentations have bottom-up and top-down influences|phenomenal space
  <span class="invalid-link-brackets">]]</span></span>. However, the phenomenal space might be <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/one-hot-encodings-are-basis-vectors-in-type-space">disentangled</a> into subspaces, say for conscious thought, <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/attention-induces-coherence">attention</a>, <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/body-movement-supports-spatial-reasoning">volition</a>.</p>
